text: The 1954 original movie was Akira Kurosawa's epic "The Seven Samurai", which was a superb film, groundbreaking in many ways (the scene in so many Westerns where the Indians come over a hill? Kurosawa!)  It was multifaceted, featuring characters with depth, morality, charisma and martial skill.  Toshiro Mifune, who plays comic relief, is brilliant. Some (many?) of the actors were also Kendo masters, so when you see them engaged in swordplay, it is the real deal.  The 1960 John Sturges remake was a piece of shallow crap, with a "yee haw!" script, two dimensional characters, and a lack of plot that happens when you take a 3h27m story and try to cram it into 2h8m. I felt genuine loss when characters died in The Seven Samurai, I found The Magnificent 7 to be boring and hackneyed.  Now they've remade the remake, with more fatalities, explosions, and random violence, even less plot and character development, and whoever did that "music" (Kanye, Kendrick, I don't care, just try something appropriate to the period).  Oh, and when Hailey Bennet says "I want righteousness... but I'll settle for revenge"?  Yeah, bullshit.  Righteous(ness) is a title bestowed upon you by others, you can't "ask for it".  Revenge is what you seek.  The word she SHOULD have used was "justice" (or "retaliation" or "retribution" or "rice crispies") any of them would have made more sense than "righteousness".  Remind me to miss this piece of cinematic garbage.

text: When I first heard they were remaking The Magnificent Seven my initial thoughts were why ? Then I saw the cast and my next feelings were excitement and anticipation to see if they could get close to the 1960 classic , A film that is one of my all time favourites.  The story doesn't stray too far from the original . Instead of Mexican bandits being the enemy . this time it's a mining tycoon and his men. The Seven are a little more multicultural too. We have Denzel Washington playing the Yul Brenner part , Ethan Hawke as the Robert Vaughn character and Chris Pratt playing the Steve McQueen role. There is also a native American Indian , a Mexican and Korean knife thrower. Despite the varied characters on show they all work really well together and you definitely care what happens to them. There is lots of great action as you would expect and none of the violence is gratuitous . My only gripe is that they didn't use the famous Elmer Bernstein soundtrack until the final credits .I think they missed a trick there.  So the big question is , is it as good as the original ? The answer is no but it's still a solid two hours of pure entertainment. MY RATING -  8 out of 10

text: It seems like you guys are upset at the diverse cast so let me school you. First and foremost African Americans have been in the US since the 1700's if you think they were never part of the "Western Movement" then you're wrong. Many fled to the West for freedom and better lively hoods. At this exact same time period the US-Mexican American War started with the US trying to take over the west and basically stealing Mexico's land. At the same time period Native Americans inhabited the land. Asians were brought during this exact same time period to build the railroads. Asian women where brought in as prostitutes during the "Cowboy Era". So yes the West was VERY VERY DIVERSE and still is today. This is why having the cast that they have was a job well done. Now I'm not happy with the representation of women but.....I can live.

text: I've seen "The Magnificent Seven," the 2016 version based from the original "Seven Samurai" & the first original one in the 1960's, and it was a really good. It's actually a much a better version than the 60's which stands out good, but they updated a little better. I enjoy the new cast and they look entertaining. Denzel Washington is clever as the leader of Seven outlaws and he's such a history. I would only take him as a clever actor than Will Smith any day. Chris Pratt is the best second man ever and he's charming and very badass at the same time. So does the rest and they did their roles good. The action scenes were fun, entertaining, and so much action that it is generic, but a good Western style like most films that are spaghetti western films. Overall, entertaining film ever.  Seven Samurai: A classic film ever by Kurosawa. The Magnificent Seven 60's: A good remake. The Magnificent Seven 10's: A very well done remake.

text: Compare this version with the one from the 60s and one things becomes immediately obvious: The politically correctness of the 2016 version:  1. The main character is a black american. 2. The driving force is the vengeance of a Woman (who in the oldfer version shows only for 5 mins and then is forgotten). 3. There's an Indian now, amongst the magnificent seven.  ... I'm surprised there isn't a homossexual amongst the magnificent seven.  I mean don't get me wrong. I'm all for having all races and sexes as protagonists in a story. But pushing them in a story that originally had none, almost seems a bit "forced"... As if there was now a law that enforced a minimum quota of women and racial minoroties in every narrative. What should be regarded as freedom and equality is becoming almost cumpolsory political correctness. This is obviously forced when it should be spontaneous.

text: A definition of harmless popcorn entertainment, this is unfortunately another remake that nobody asked for but it got made and it is kinda there. It is not bad , it is not good, it is somehow mediocre and forgettable.   What worked in the movie were performances except Chris Pratt who felt like Chris Pratt in a western and not the character. They had some nice chemistry, back and forth exchange and they worked as the saviours. It looks good as filming locations really shine, it has decent production values and action is fun to watch. But that is it. It is nowhere near the material that Tarantino does with the genre, you have seen it all before, bad guy is so stereotypical to the point you can hear him exhale when he smokes cigar, some western cliches are inevitable i guess even here, you do not care unfortunately for anyone including the magnificent seven because they are underdeveloped and rushed into the story plus film lacks the emotional depth.  It is disposable afternoon entertainment, but if you want more from the genre than cookie cutter story than pass. 3/5

text: Growing up as a teenager, I watched a ton of western movies from Dead Tombstone to 3:10 to Yuma. However, when I first saw the modern version of The Magnificent 7, it became my all time favorite! I fell in love with the storyline and am obsessed with the action stunt performances. I liked the movie so much, that one day mom and dad bought it for me to watch any time I like. Whenever I see the ending, I feel sad, but on the other hand touched. The movie's message is very true and meaningful to me. That's what makes this story so special. Of all the characters however, my favorite is Ethan Hawke. I just like both his physical appearance and attitudes.

text: For those who don't know, the original Magnificent 7 television show was based on the Japanese movie Seven Samurai. This Magnificent 7 movie was based on the 2010 Japanese movie 13 Assassins. There's lots of American movies that are based on Asian movies like The Departed based on the Chinese movie Infernal Affairs. The Ring based on the Japanese movie Ringu. The Grudge based on the Japanese movie Ju-On. The Eye based on the Chinese movie The Eye or Jian Gui. And so many others. I'm a huge fan of Asian cinema so there's lots of American movies borrowed from Asian directors.

text: What I loved in this movie is how this fictional rendition of the American West, mirrors and/or makes homages to the real life people and history of the Old West.   Sam Chisolm (US Marshal) = Bass Reeves (Deputy US Marshal)  Josh Faraday (Gambler) = John "Doc" Holliday (Gambler)   Goodnight Robicheaux (Ex-Confederate Sharpshooter) = Charles Goodnight (Ex-Confederate & Cattle Rancher)   Jack Horne (Mountain Man & Tracker) = Tom Horn (US Army Scout, Pinkerton Detective, & Hired Assassin)  Billy Rocks (Asian Immigrant) = Cant find any person in particular, but he does represent the mass immigration of Asians to the United States; as well as their contributions to diversifying the western frontier.   Vasquez (Mexican Outlaw) = Tiburcio Vásquez (Mexican/Californian Outlaw)   Red Harvest (Commanche Warrior) = Possibly Quanah Parker (Comanche Warrior/Chief) yet he could also mirror other Native American Renegades such as "The Apache Kid".   Bartholomew Bogue (Corrupt Industrialist) = The multiple aristocrats and bureaucrats which desired to modernize the frontier and acquire it's natural resources (lumber, cattle, mining, etc.)   Denali (Commanche Warrior who works for Bartholomew Bogue) = The various Native Americans who volunteered and/or were forced to serve the United States Military during the Indian Wars.   Blackstone Detectives (Private Detectives) = Pinkerton National Detective Agency (Private Detectives)

text: Watch the original Magnificent Seven. They didn't go for including token minorities randomly and make an action movie with a western skin, it was a classic. It knew how to give each of the seven men a strong and different personality without having them be different video game classes. There are many types of western movies (traditionnal, revisionist, spaghetti, zapata) and the golden age was from the late 1940s to the end of the 1960s. After that the western genre pretty much died, with a small revival in the 90s with Unforgiven and Tombstone, but they won't be the same, they don't have the same spirit today.  Good traditionnal westerns (with John Wayne and such): Rio Bravo, the Searchers, Warlock, High Noon, Red River, Magnificent Seven, Ride the high country, True Grit, the Sons of Katie Elder, El Dorado, etc  Good spaghetti westerns (from Italian directors): the Dollar trilogy, Once upon a time in the west, Duck you sucker, Death rides a horse  Among the Dollar Trilogy of course is The Good, the Bad and the Ugly, which is perhaps today the best-known western, and western stereotypes of gun duels and all come a lot from this one. It is also my favorite western movie, and I am a big fan.
